# rrdoctor Verify Loop

Use this rule when editing a research repository for reproducibility, Artifact
Evaluation, public release, notebook cleanup, dependency documentation, data
provenance, citation metadata, or coding-agent remediation.

rrdoctor is the grader. Cursor is the editor. Do not weaken rrdoctor checks to
make a task pass.

Run the loop:

```bash
uvx rrdoctor scan . --format json --output baseline.json
uvx rrdoctor plan . --output plan.md
# Work through plan.md without weakening checks.
uvx rrdoctor scan . --baseline baseline.json --fail-on-new error
```

The final command is the definition of done. If it reports a new error, continue
fixing from the finding and re-run the gate.

The default scan is static and safe for untrusted repositories: it does not
install, import, build, or execute target code.

For trusted repositories only, use the dynamic gate:

```bash
uvx rrdoctor verify . --run --timeout 600 --fail-on error
```

Prioritize high-signal reproducibility blockers: missing run paths, unpinned or
missing dependency metadata, local-only data paths, stale notebook outputs,
missing citation/data/results provenance, and seed flags that do not actually
seed randomness.
